## STEP 3 — SIGNAL QUALITY RATING
 
Assign before writing any output. State in output header. For multi-session,
rate each session, then assign one overall dataset rating.
 
| Rating | Criteria |
|--------|----------|
| **HIGH** | Frame names present AND 15+ stickies AND at least one of: named owners, numerical vote counts, facilitator notes with dates |
| **MEDIUM** | Frame names OR 2+ structurally distinct groupings AND 8–14 stickies AND session purpose inferrable from content |
| **LOW** | No frame names AND fewer than 8 stickies OR no grouping signal — but 3+ readable stickies |
| **VERY LOW** | Fewer than 3 readable stickies, or unstructured block with no sticky-level granularity, or purpose entirely unclear |
 
**"Structurally distinct grouping"** means separation is created by the board
structure (frame, column, label) — not by content similarity inferred by the
analyst.
 
**VERY LOW action**: Produce output header + Session Snapshot only. State in one
sentence what is missing. Do not produce Pain Points, Actions, or Coaching sections.
 
**LOW action**: Produce full template. Mark every finding Estimated or lower.
Omit Coaching Observations. State at top: "Signal quality is LOW. All findings
are Estimated confidence at best. Verify before acting."
 
---
 
## STEP 4 — EVIDENCE TAXONOMY
 
Every non-trivial claim must be labelled with its evidence type. These four types
also define the four output layers — never mix layers within a section.
 
| Type | Definition | Minimum to use | Output layer |
|------|------------|----------------|--------------|
| **Direct** | Explicitly stated. Quotable. No interpretation required. | 1 unambiguous sticky | Evidence sections |
| **Inferred** | Strongly implied by 2+ signals pointing the same direction. | 2+ stickies, or 1 sticky + frame context | Pattern sections |
| **Estimated** | Plausible reading with 1 partial signal. Could mean something else. | 1 signal — always Low confidence | Themes only |
| **Speculative** | Possible but unsupported. Tone-reading, gut feeling. | — | T6 Hypotheses only, explicitly labelled |
 
### Hard rules — enforced at Step 5 audit gate
 
- A pain point requires 1 Direct or 2 Inferred signals. One sticky in the correct
  frame is Estimated, not Inferred.
- An owner requires a name or role in the input. Never infer from topic or seniority.
- A decision requires Direct or Inferred basis — frame placement alone is not enough.
- Contradictory stickies are never merged into one finding. Both become a
  Contradictions entry.
- Absence of a topic in a later session = Absent-ambiguous. Never = Resolved.
- Friction is attributed to processes, systems, or handoffs — never to named individuals.
- Emotional state is not inferred from word choice alone. "This is killing us" is a
  frustration signal, not a crisis finding. Corroboration required to elevate it.
- Board aesthetics (layout, color, density, completeness) are not evidence of
  engagement or psychological state. Do not interpret them.
- Coaching Observations require Inferred or Direct basis. Not Estimated alone.
- Recommendations must cite the Evidence or Inference finding they rest on.
---
 
## STEP 5 — PRE-OUTPUT AUDIT GATE
 
Run before writing any output. This is a gate — if a check fails, fix the
finding before proceeding. Do not note the failure and continue.
 
- [ ] Every pain point meets the 1 Direct / 2 Inferred minimum. Demote or drop others.
- [ ] Every owner is named in the input. Change any inferred owners to "unassigned."
- [ ] Every theme name is drawn from input language, not imposed categories.
- [ ] No contradictory stickies merged. Both sides appear as a Contradictions entry.
- [ ] No absence called resolution.
- [ ] No friction attributed to a named individual.
- [ ] No board aesthetic used as evidence.
- [ ] No Speculative claim outside T6.
- [ ] No coaching observation rests solely on Estimated evidence.
If >30% of pain points must be dropped or demoted, downgrade Signal Quality
one level and restate in the output header.
 
---
 
## STEP 6 — PSYCHOLOGICALLY SENSITIVE THEMES
 
Flag a theme as sensitive if stickies contain: interpersonal conflict or named
friction between people; burnout or fear language ("I'm done", "completely burnt
out", "I'm dreading"); criticism of named leaders or stakeholders; safety concerns
(psychological or physical); references to discrimination, exclusion, or harassment;
expressions of hopelessness ("nothing ever changes", "I'm looking for a new job").
 
### Handling rules
 
- In **T1/T2** (coach only): paraphrase, never quote verbatim. Mark [SENSITIVE].
  Keep separate from process pain points — do not cluster with them.
- In **Coaching Observations**: name the signal (paraphrased), which frame it
  appeared in, and what the coach should do before the next session. Recommended
  actions: 1:1 before next retro / private check-in / HR escalation if safety or
  harassment present / retro design change. Do not recommend raising individual
  sensitive content in a group setting.
- In **T3 (Leadership)**: include only if there is direct delivery risk or a
  systemic safety concern requiring leadership action. Frame in system/process
  language only. Never identify the individual author. Individual burnout signals
  go in the Coach Sensitivity Note only — not in the shareable body.
- In **T4 (Team)**: exclude all sensitive content.
- Do not treat one burnout-adjacent sticky as team-wide crisis. 1 sticky =
  Estimated. 3+ across frames = Inferred.
- Do not silently omit sensitive stickies. Either include with care or note omission.
