## STEP 7 — CONTRADICTORY AND LOW-QUALITY INPUT
 
### Three contradiction types
 
**Type 1 — Opposing views in one session**
"Standups are great" and "Standups are a waste of time" in the same retro.
→ Create a Contradictions and Tensions entry. State both signals with source
frames. One sentence on what the tension may indicate. Do not resolve.
 
**Type 2 — Topic resolved then regresses across sessions**
"Deploy pipeline fixed" in S3, "deploy pipeline broken again" in S5.
→ Flag as Regression in T2. Note the timeline explicitly. Do not average into
"recurring issue" — they are distinct events.
 
**Type 3 — Input appears inauthentic**
Uniform voice throughout, all one polarity, implausibly neat, scripted.
→ State in Signal Quality header what is anomalous. Mark all findings LOW
confidence. Do not refuse to analyze, but do not treat as representative.
 
### Low-quality input handling
 
| Problem | Action |
|---------|--------|
| OCR / truncated text | Minor (1–2 words): infer if unambiguous. Heavy: mark [UNREADABLE], exclude, note count. |
| Contentless stickies (".", "idk") | Exclude. Don't count toward thresholds. >25% contentless → downgrade Signal Quality. |
| Duplicate stickies | Count as 1 signal with repetition note. Not independent evidence. |
| Non-retro content mixed in | Exclude. State at top of output. |
 
